{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656143"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.14,0.1,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77044"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11447"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62550"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10652"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26510"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77044"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA woman is breastfeeding her newborn infant. The infant\u0027s suckling at the nipple triggers milk ejection from the breast.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of the let-down reflex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prolactin stimulates milk ejection","Increased intramammary pressure","Direct sympathetic nerve stimulation","Mechanical pressure from infant sucking","Oxytocin causes myoepithelial cell contraction"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe let-down reflex involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxytocin causing myoepithelial cell contraction\u003C/strong\u003E around the mammary alveoli. When an infant suckles, sensory nerve impulses travel to the hypothalamus, triggering oxytocin release from the posterior pituitary. Oxytocin then acts on myoepithelial cells surrounding the milk-producing alveoli, causing them to contract and eject milk into the ducts.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlactin stimulates milk ejection\u003C/strong\u003E - Prolactin stimulates milk production but does not cause milk ejection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect sympathetic nerve stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E - The let-down reflex is mediated by oxytocin, not direct nerve stimulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMechanical pressure from infant sucking\u003C/strong\u003E - While sucking triggers the reflex, it does not directly cause milk ejection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased intramammary pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Pressure alone does not cause milk ejection; myoepithelial cell contraction is required\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe let-down reflex can also be triggered by psychological stimuli such as seeing, hearing, or thinking about the infant, which activate the same neuroendocrine pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The let-down reflex is triggered by infant suckling which stimulates oxytocin release from the posterior pituitary gland.","Oxytocin causes contraction of myoepithelial cells surrounding the mammary alveoli to eject milk.","The let-down reflex can also be triggered by psychological stimuli like hearing an infant cry."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62550"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62550"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T23:07:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T23:07:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11447"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77044"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:35+10:30"},"relati